1. c4{ Welcome to Part 2 of the Neo-Catalan! For those who don’t know me, I’m Sam Shankland, an American 2700+ player, and a longtime Chessable author. This is my 10th course and my 9th on the opening. Most notably, I previously covered the Neo-Catalan  Part I , and now it is time to begin the middle step of the journey.     Part I focused on all of Black’s attempts to treat the move 1.  c4  as if he was playing against 1.  d4 , and that we are just using a different move order. Indeed, the main three setups that I covered were based upon Black bringing his bishop to  g7  in the style of the King’s Indian or the Grunfeld, playing a setup with ... e6  and ... d5  in the style of the true Catalan or Queen’s Gambit Declined, and playing with ... c6  and ... d5  in the style of the Slav. For the most part, I think I did a very good job putting Black’s position under pressure and fighting for an opening advantage.     In particular, I really made good use of the 1.  c4  move order, often later pushing  d2 - d4  to transpose into favorable versions of 1.  d4  lines while taking advantage of avoiding some of his better equalizing attempts by holding back the queen’s pawn until the time was right. To that effect, Part I looks like a super-charged Catalan to me, notably superior to what White can expect in a normal Catalan with a 1.  d4  move order. It would be great if that was all there was to it, and the Neo-Catalan was simply better than the proper Catalan. But in chess and life, almost nothing is free, and the price we pay for having a generally superior version of the Catalan against Black’s attempts to keep the game in 1.  d4  territory is that we allow 1...  c5  and 1...  e5 , both of which are serious moves that fight well for equality.     Each of these moves has enough lines to cover a whole course, and part 2 will address 1...  c5 . The Symmetrical English is Black’s best attempt to keep the game solid and level. In a lot of ways, the positions feel very similar to what Black is trying to do in 1.  e4   e5  lines. Black will have some extremely solid options here, like the Berlin or the Petroff against 1.  e4 , but he also has some more dynamic and double-edged tries, as one might see in the Archangel or Cozio systems.     From our perspective, it’s quite nice that Black’s direct attempts to equalize are quite limited in comparison to what one would see in the Spanish. Once we have committed to 2.  g3 , which is our move for this course and will also be our move for the final one covering 1...  e5 , Black will very likely follow suit with some combination of the moves  g7 - g6 ,  Bf8 - g7 , and  Nb8 - c6  in one move order or another, which will reach the Mainline Symmetrical English.     While the positions may look dull at first glance, Black is unable to play copycat forever because then we will be able to push  d2 - d4  before he can play  d7 - d5 . For the most part, once we have committed our knight to  f3 , Black will have to either play  Ng8 - f6  in response, allowing us to take a bigger share of the center and imbalance the game with  d2 - d4 , or he will have to develop his  g8 -knight in another way. All of this helps make sure the game does not fizzle to some dry equality, and I believe I have managed to give White a reasonably fresh, playable position just about everywhere.     Prior to reaching a normal Symmetrical English, Black can also aim for a quick  d7 - d5 , either with or without  e7 - e6  first. These positions are more direct but also more imbalanced, and I think I have found ways to put his position under a fair amount of practical pressure. Undoubtedly, as is the case in any mainline opening, Black will be able to objectively equalize in several spots. Since this cannot be avoided, the next best thing we can do is aim to make him work hard for that equality and then for the equality to still be playable. To this extent, we have to use our human judgment to evaluate which positions the computer calls equal feel more pleasant for White, and which ones do not. I generally think this is something I am quite good at, but I have my biases like anyone else.     There were at least 3 spots in this repertoire where I reached a position where Black will be left with an isolated pawn, and no other major imbalances, and I overruled the machine and said White was better in human practice. Perhaps this will not appeal so much to someone who loves attacking kings and doesn’t care much for technical chess, but it would be the kind of position I would be delighted to reach. It's always a daunting task to try to find recommendations for White against extremely solid lines. I know that this course was much harder to write than it was to cover the Berlin for Black! In a lot of ways, it feels like the deck is rigged against us, as not only is Black equalizing in all mainline openings, but in this particular section, he is trying to do so while keeping a more symmetrical position. Still, I am satisfied with what I came up with, and I sincerely hope this repertoire helps bring a lot of points to everyone who gives it a try.     It’s time for training to begin! The below lines are covered in the course. }
1. c5
2. g3
