5. Nf3( { Finally, it is time to start coverage of the mainline Symmetrical English! This position can be reached by a number of move orders, and seems very likely to arise after the game begins with   }1.c4 c5 2.g3 { . } )
5. e5{ One of the most common options for Black is to simply set up a Botvinnik development scheme with  e7 - e5  and  Ng8 - e7 . For a long time, this was considered his best option, but in the modern era, this is not such a common way of playing. In my opinion, that is for good reason, and I like White's chances of fighting for an advantage here more than what he gets against some of Black's other setups. }( 5...d6 6.O-O e5 7.a3 { transposes to the 5...  Nge7  move order. } )
6. a3{ I like this move a lot. White is hoping to quickly aim for queenside expansion with  b2 - b4 , taking advantage of Black blunting his own bishop on  g7 . We see this theme a lot in other lines as well- when Black tries to take a lot of space in the center while falling behind in development,  a2 - a3  and  b2 - b4  is a good way to try to put him under pressure. }
6. d6( { Black can always push  d7 - d6 . Now, White has options apart from castling here, but to keep our repertoire consistent, I believe we have to castle. This is because Black could force us to reach that position by using a   }5...d6 6.O-O e5 { move order. } )
7. O-O
7. a5{ In general, I think Black should be making some attempt to stop us from getting  b2 - b4  in. Then, he ultimately can hope for  Ng8 - e7 ,  O-O ,  Bc8 - e6 , and the  d6 - d5  break will give him a nice space advantage. In order to get  d6 - d5  in, he absolutely must prevent us from putting a pawn on  b4 . But, this is a lot of moves in a row for Black, and we get to fight back against this plan in the meantime. }
8. d3
8. Nge7
9. Ne1{ The beginning of a maneuver directed at consolidating the  d5 -square. }
9. Be6{ Now, the main move by far is  Ne1 - c2 , forcing immediate complications. Black will have to respond with  d6 - d5  right away, but I am not entirely safisfied with White's position there. I even won a nice game with Black from that point back in 2019. I think we can look in another direction. }
10. Bg5{ This move is not super popular and is not mentioned in Vigorito's course for Black covering the Symmetrical English. But, it is White's best scoring option by some margin, and recently has been the choice of Abdusattorov, and I definitely think it is the best move. }
10. O-O
11. Bxe7{ I like this blunt move. White changes the character of the game completely. }
11. Nxe7( 11...Qxe7 12.Nc2 { By taking with the queen on  e7 , we are very confident that Black will not be able to get  d6 - d5  in under any circumstances. White has an easy play on the queenside with  Ra1 - b1 ,  b2 - b4 , and  Nc3 - d5  coming in short order. } )
12. Nc2{ Once again, it is now or never for the  d6 - d5  break. White is ready for  Nc2 - e3  next. }
12. d5( { This feels the most consistent to me. }12...f5 13.Ne3⩲ { White has a nice position thanks to his control of the light-squares. He plops a knight on  d5  next and aims for  Ra1 - b1  and  b2 - b4 , while Black's  g7 -bishop does not impress. } )
13. cxd5{ Now we trade everything. }
13. Nxd5
14. Nxd5
14. Bxd5
15. Bxd5
15. Qxd5
16. e4{ We see why it was so important to trade our dark-squared bishop for a knight. White has simplified the position down to a good knight vs bad bishop scenario, and he should be better with  Ne3 - d5  coming next. Eventually, he can hope to open the queenside with  b2 - b4  at the right moment. }
