6. cxd4{ This is the old main move, and in my opinion, a very reasonable chance to fight for equality. I have played this position myself from the black side more than once. }
7. Nb5{ Black should be careful not to allow a check on  d6 . }
7. d5
8. cxd5{ Now, once upon a time, checking on  a5  was thought to be Black's best move. It is not that easy to deal with and remains a viable attempt to fight for equality, but I think ... exd5  should be considered the main move. }
8. Qa5+
9. Nd2{ This is a surprising and important move. White needs to open up the  g2 -bishop to make trouble. }
9. Qxb5
10. dxc6
10. Ne7{ The crux of Black's plan. He does not bother trying to take the c-pawn, and instead encourages us to take on  b7 , accelerating his development and neutralizing our  g2 -bishop. We need an important move here to avoid becoming worse, but it works out very nicely. }
11. a4
11. Qb6{ Now, if we did not have the foresight to play the surprising  Nf3 - d2  instead of the more natural  Bc1 - d2 , Black would be totally fine here. But our next move changes things and begins a forcing continuation. }
12. Nc4{ The purpose is to move the queen away from  b7 . }
12. Qb4+
13. Bd2
13. Qxc4
14. cxb7
14. Bxb7
15. Bxb7
15. Rb8
16. Rc1{ The dust is settling, and White has a bishop pair and an outside pawn majority. By contrast, Black has some activity on the b-file and a well-advanced  d4 -pawn. This position is known to be nice for White, but accuracy is needed. For the purposes of the Quickstarter, the line ends with this move. For a more in-depth analysis, see the lines starting from  here.  }
