1. c4
1. c5
2. g3{ Black has tried a ton of moves here, but I think his only serious plans are those involving ... e6  and ... d5 , ... Nf6  and ... d5 , or bringing the bishop to  g7  and reaching a mainline Symmetrical English. Still, it is worthwhile to know what to do against some of his other options. }
2. d6{ Of course,  d7 - d6  is possible at more or less any juncture - but it is non-committal and extremely likely to transpose to something else. }
3. Bg2
3. e5( 3...g6 4.Nf3 { This will promptly transpose to the Mainline Symmetrical English section. } )( 3...Nc6 4.Nc3 { Black doesn't have any serious moves that don't involve ... Nf6 , ... g6 , or ... e5 . This will transpose to other lines. } )
4. Nc3{ Now, I think Black really should play some combination of ... g6 , ... Nc6 , ... Nge7 , and ... Bg7  in the next several moves. The only possible alternative option I can see is to try to develop the bishop to  e7  instead, but I find this quite poor. }
4. Be7
5. e3{ I like this move a lot. In general, it's good to know that the plan of setting up with  e2 - e3  and  Ng1 - e2  makes a lot of sense against a combination of  c7 - c5  and  e7 - e5 - we saw something  a bit like this  in Part I against the King's Indian where Black played an early ... c5 .     In our repertoire, when Black plays intelligently, he can force us to make up our minds with our  g1 -knight before he touches his e-pawn, and then play  e7 - e5  only after we have committed to  Ng1 - f3 . Here, we can take advantage of him showing his cards too soon. }
5. Nc6
6. Nge2{ White has an easy position and can play with either  d2 - d4  or  Nc3 - d5  next, depending on what Black does. We will see a fantastic game from Kramnik in the illustrative games section in a similar position. }
