1. c4
1. c5
2. g3{ Black has tried a ton of moves here, but I think his only serious plans are those involving ... e6  and ... d5 , ... Nf6  and ... d5 , or bringing the bishop to  g7  and reaching a mainline Symmetrical English. Still, it is worthwhile to know what to do against some of his other options. }
2. h5{ This move is not totally ridiculous now that we have committed to 2.  g3 , but I still find it hard to believe. }
3. Nf3{ This feels most natural by far. White stops any hope of  h5 - h4  and continues along with normal development. }
3. Nc6( 3...g6 4.Bg2 Bg7 5.Nc3 Nc6 { This transposes to ... h5  in the mainline Symmetrical English section. } )
4. Nc3
4. d6
5. Bg2
5. Bg4{ I guess Black could consider pressuring the knight directly with the hope of getting  h5 - h4  in, but I don't buy it. }( 5...e5 { If our main plan to punish Black's flank lunges is to push for  d2 - d4 , it makes some sense for him to prevent us from doing so directly. Still, I really do not buy this setup for him. }6.e3! { Not especially subtle.  d2 - d4  comes next anyway, and the center opening further can only help White. } )
6. h3
6. Bxf3
7. Bxf3{ White is always ready to meet  h5 - h4  with  g3 - g4 , and he looks to have a good version of the 6...  Bg4  lines in the mainline Symmetrical English.  h7 - h5  is really out of place and costs black a tempo. }
