3. Qxd5( 3...Nf6 4.Bg2 { More ambitious moves are possible, but I like this one for its simplicity. We transpose to the 2...  Nf6  lines. } )
4. Nf3
4. Nc6
5. Bg2
5. Nf6
6. Nc3{ Now, Black should bring the queen back to  d8 , transposing to a line we will see later on. }
6. Qd7{ If Black insists on not going back home, this is the queen's best square. There is some logic behind it - he wants to play ... e5 , ... Bd6 , and then ... b6  and ... Bb7 . Once he has completed this development scheme, the queen will look better on  d7  than on  d8 . Still, I find this to be very suspicious. }( 6...Qd8 { This transposes to the 2...  Nf6  chapter where Black meets  Nc3  with ... Nf6 . } )
7. d3{ I like this move a lot. We make sure to get the bishop to  g5  right away. }
7. e5
8. Bg5
8. Be7{ It's hard to imagine anything else. Now, we can take advantage of the bishop being on  e7 . }
9. Rc1{ Since the bishop could not go to  d6  to overprotect the  e5 -pawn, Black is always unable to play  b7 - b6  on pain of  Nf3xe5 . So, how does he get his bishop out? He is at serious risk of losing his  c5 -pawn directly to  Nc3 - a4  or  Bg5xf6  followed by  Nc3 - e4 . }
