7. Nxd4
7. O-O
8. Nc3
8. Nxd4{ This has been one of Black's most popular moves in the past. This does not speak well for the intelligence of humanity! }
9. Qxd4{ Black's position is absolutely horrendous. He will never push  b6 , never play  d5 . So how does he ever develop his bishop? I guess he can play  d6 . Then he has to overprotect his  b7 -pawn. How exactly? You can't play  Rb8  with the  a7 -pawn hanging. So you have to burn another tempo on  a6 . In the meantime, White will continue with  Rf1 - d1 ,  b2 - b3 , and  Bc1 - a3  to his  d6 -pawn. Let's see a sample variation of how the game might continue. }
9. a6( { This is Black's best scoring move, where he manages to make 30%. While this is a low number, it's higher than I would have anticipated! }9...d6 10.Rd1 { Black has nothing better than  a7 - a6  here, transposing to 9...  a6 . } )
10. Rd1
10. d6
11. b3
11. Qc7( 11...Rb8 12.Ba3 { Black's position is collapsing both strategically and tactically. } )
12. Ba3( { It is a very bad sign that my computer wants }12...e5 { , which critically weakens the d5-square. } )( 12...Rd8 { feels more human to me. But after }13.Na4! { Black is unable to prevent an invasion on  b6 . } )
