[Round "?"]
[White "2) 2...e6 "]
[Black "3...d5 4.cxd5 exd5 #4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c5
2. g3
2. e6{ With this move, Black is aiming to play some kind of a Tarrasch. We will eventually transpose to a 1.  d4  line, but quite a good one for White as I believe Black cannot really hope to equalize with the Tarrasch if White avoids the move  Nb1 - c3 . }
3. Nf3{ I like this move more than  Bf1 - g2 , as I want to be able to immediately take on  d5  and push  d2 - d4 . }( { • }3.Bg2 { This move order is okay too, but I find it a little less convincing. After }3...d5 4.cxd5 exd5 5.Nf3 ( 5.d4 cxd4! { White is not able to take back with the knight, and Black can complicate the game. } )5...d4 { This move is actually a little annoying. After a later  e2 - e3 , I don't like that taking on  d4  would lead to a symmetrical structure instead of a Reversed Benoni. }( { • }3.Bg2 d5 4.Nf3 d4 { Black has this option to transpose to the Reverse Benoni, as seen in Part }{ 1. I stand by my work there, but I think that line leaves him with better chances to equalize than what we will see here. } ) )
3. d5{ This is, of course, the consistent follow-up. }
4. cxd5
4. exd5
5. d4{ Now, we have transposed directly to a Tarrasch defense that could just as easily have been seen from a 1.  d4  move order. I did cover  this line  already in Part 3 of my 1.  d4  repertoire, and while most of the analysis stood up very well, I was not totally thrilled with what I gave in the 9.  a3  line. Recent engine developments have shown Black has better chances to fight for equality there than I had initially given credit for. So, I have simply copied and pasted everything up to move 9 in the mainline, at which point I have chosen to go in a different direction. }
5. Nc6
6. Bg2
6. Nf6
7. O-O
7. c4{ Of course, gaining space on the queenside and trying to avoid the isolated pawn is sensible enough, but also not equalizing. After the natural }
8. b3{ Black is unable to maintain the pawn on  c4 . }
8. Be7
9. bxc4
9. dxc4
10. Na3{ The  c4 -pawn will fall sooner rather than later, and once more White is very happy that he had not yet committed his knight to  c3 . }
