3. Nf3{ I like this move more than  Bf1 - g2 , as I want to be able to immediately take on  d5  and push  d2 - d4 . }( { • }3.Bg2 { This move order is okay too, but I find it a little less convincing. After }3...d5 4.cxd5 exd5 5.Nf3 ( 5.d4 cxd4! { White is not able to take back with the knight, and Black can complicate the game. } )5...d4 { This move is actually a little annoying. After a later  e2 - e3 , I don't like that taking on  d4  would lead to a symmetrical structure instead of a Reversed Benoni. }( { • }3.Bg2 d5 4.Nf3 d4 { Black has this option to transpose to the Reverse Benoni, as seen in Part }{ 1. I stand by my work there, but I think that line leaves him with better chances to equalize than what we will see here. } ) )
3. d5{ This is, of course, the consistent follow-up. }
4. cxd5
4. exd5
5. d4{ Now, we have transposed directly to a Tarrasch defense that could just as easily have been seen from a 1.  d4  move order. I did cover  this line  already in Part 3 of my 1.  d4  repertoire, and while most of the analysis stood up very well, I was not totally thrilled with what I gave in the 9.  a3  line. Recent engine developments have shown Black has better chances to fight for equality there than I had initially given credit for. So, I have simply copied and pasted everything up to move 9 in the mainline, at which point I have chosen to go in a different direction. }
5. Nc6
6. Bg2
6. Nf6
7. O-O
7. Be7( { This is the main move by far. }7...cxd4 8.Nxd4 { transposes to the 5...  Nf6  variation. } )
8. dxc5
8. Bxc5{ Up to here, everything has been copied from the 1.  d4  repertoire. Now, I gave  a2 - a3   here originally . It is not a bad move and White has good chances to fight for an edge, but I decided to update it and look in a different direction. }
9. Bg5{ This is common enough, but White's next move is where the real surprise comes. }
9. O-O{ This is definitely Black's best move. }
10. Qc1{ I like this move a lot, which has been played just one time in the database out of nearly 300 games.  Qc2  might look more natural and has seen a fair amount of play, but for a very specific reason, I believe  c1  is the better square. I really like that Black is forced to bring his bishop back to  e7 , which is obviously a more passive square than  b6  would be. }( { • }10.Qc2 { This looks more natural, but I dislike that Black can put his bishop on  b6 . }10...Bb6! 11.Nc3 d4! 12.Ne4 Bf5! { This pin is annoying, and the reason I think the queen belongs on  c1  instead. } )( { • }10.Nc3 { This is the main move, but rather than ... Be6 , which would transpose to the 9...  Be6  line, I think Black is very close to equality with }10...d4 11.Ne4 Be7  )
10. Be7{ My computer is very insistent that this is Black's best move. It is surely right, but this is also a move we should be very happy to see since it is passive and moving backwards. }
11. Nc3
11. d4
12. Rd1{ Black might just lose his  d4 -pawn. Already, we are threatening to take it and follow up with  e2 - e3 . }
12. h6{ Nothing else makes much sense. }
13. Nxd4
13. Nxd4
14. Be3
14. Nxe2+
15. Nxe2
15. Qa5
16. h3{ White keeps the bishop off of  g4 . It's unclear how Black plans on getting his queenside out with the unopposed  g2 -bishop lasering down on the long diagonal. }
