12. h6
13. Be3{ Up to this point, we have been following one of the lines of Jorden Van Foreest's Tarrasch course here on Chessable.     I have to give him huge props for a job well done, making the Tarrasch seem reasonably playable, and he even covered this very rare  Qc1  move. But here, he only considered what happens if White takes on  f6 . Retreating to  e3  to preserve the bishop pair feels much more natural, and I think White looks a little better. We probably will have to eventually lose a tempo with  Qc1 - c2  to play  Ra1 - c1  and complete development, but I think it was a tempo well worth losing because Black's bishop was forced to  e7 .     The machine is not that impressed with White's position, but in human terms, it looks really good to me. Black has no counterplay, no means to liquidate his isolani, and no means to simplify to anything easier. And he has to get here in the first place! }
