3. Bg2
3. d5{ One of the most direct things Black can do is to try to take as big a share of the center as possible, and quickly pushing  d7 - d5  is a very natural way to try to make this happen. }
4. cxd5{ Of course we take on  d5 . }
4. Nxd5
5. Nf3
5. Nc6{ Nothing else makes any sense. Now, I think we should challenge the  d5 -knight immediately. }
6. Nc3{ Now, Black's two main moves here, by far, are  g6  and  Nc7 , both of which give him very good chances to fight for equality. But he has some extraneous options we should also be ready for. }
6. e6{ This feels a bit weird to me, but it is not totally ridiculous. If White were to push  d2 - d4  here, he would transpose to another variation of the English that leads to a slightly uncomfortable endgame for Black, but one that has been well studied and analyzed and basically worked out to a draw. I like being more patient. }
7. O-O
7. Nf6{ This strange move is my computer's recommendation. }
8. e3{ I like this move. It is very direct- White wants  d4  next. It makes sense to blow up the center when Black is wasting time with his knight like this. }
8. Be7{ Nobody has ever played anything else. }
9. d4
9. O-O
10. dxc5
10. Bxc5
11. a3{ White has a nice version of the Queen's Gambit Accepted, against which he normally would never have his bishop on  g2 . Once  b2 - b4  and  Bc1 - b2  comes next, White's bishops will be much better than their black counterparts, and Black's coordination is really suffering. }
