[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c5
2. g3
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. d5{ One of the most direct things Black can do is to try to take as big a share of the center as possible, and quickly pushing  d7 - d5  is a very natural way to try to make this happen. }
4. cxd5{ Of course we take on  d5 . }
4. Nxd5
5. Nf3
5. Nc6{ Nothing else makes any sense. Now, I think we should challenge the  d5 -knight immediately. }
6. Nc3{ Now, Black's two main moves here, by far, are  g6  and  Nc7 , both of which give him very good chances to fight for equality. But he has some extraneous options we should also be ready for. }
6. g6{ In modern times, this has emerged as the main move. Black is basically trying to play White in the Symmetrical English, employing the exact same moves we are using with colors reversed if he instead develops with ... Nf6 , ... g6 , and ... Bg7 . Being a tempo down means he certainly cannot hope to be better playing this way, but it is a very good attempt to equalize.  d2 - d4  more or less always leads to the position fizzling out, and it's not easy for White to find another way to challenge Black's space advantage.     Ultimately, I think Black is fine here, but I am satisfied that I came up with a way to at least put him under pressure and make his life a little tougher than the current state of theory suggests it should be. }
7. Qa4{ I quite like this rare and tricky move. Black should be fine if he really knows what he is doing, but the positions are hard to handle and it says a lot that nobody has really played them well yet in human practice. }
7. e6{ This was Caruana's choice against me. It's not a terrible move and Black is solid, but definitely a little worse. }
8. Nxd5{ This is even stronger than  Nf3 - e5 , grabbing the bishop pair. The latter was my choice and I got a slight advantage, but wasn't able to get much more than that and only managed to put Black under minimal pressure before eventually drawing the game. }
8. Qxd5{ This was the move that bothered me during the game, but somehow I had missed a very simple and powerful idea. }
9. Nh4
9. Qd6
10. Bxc6+{ White can comfortably shatter the structure, and doesn't have to worry about his light squares. The  c8 -bishop being blocked in by the  e6 -pawn is heavily in our favor. }
10. bxc6
11. d3
11. Bg7
12. Rb1{ White has an incredibly straightforward plan.  O-O ,  Bc1 - e3 ,  b2 - b3  to keep everything safe. Put a bunch of pieces on the c-file and take the c-pawn. And Black is more or less powerless to stop it. }
