7. Qa4{ I quite like this rare and tricky move. Black should be fine if he really knows what he is doing, but the positions are hard to handle and it says a lot that nobody has really played them well yet in human practice. }
7. Bg7{ Of course, this is Black's most natural and strongest move, and the one we should expect. }
8. Ng5{ The pressure on the long diagonal makes it hard for Black to deal with the threat to his knight. }
8. Nb6
9. Bxc6+{ Of course. }
9. bxc6
10. Qxc6+
10. Bd7
11. Qxc5{ Somehow I have a hard time believing Black has enough for two pawns here, although the machine seems to think he does if he finds a bunch of only moves in a row. }
11. h6
12. Nf3
12. Rc8
13. Qa5{ The best square for the queen. We make sure Black cannot make an aggressive move like  Nb6 - c4  without allowing a queen exchange. }
13. Bh3{ We would surely be better if we could castle. }
14. Rg1{ White prevents  Bg2 , and he is ready for  d2 - d3  and  Bd2  next. If that happens, it is very hard to see what Black can hope to get for his material. }
14. Qd6{ Another only move to maintain a tenable position. Black's point is that the generally desirable  d2 - d3  runs into trouble after  Rc8 - c5 . }
15. d4
15. O-O( { Now and only now, Black castles. It strikes me as very hard to play like this for him. }15...Bxd4? 16.Nb5!+- {   }15...Nc4 16.Qd5+-  )
16. Bf4
16. Qe6
17. Ne5
17. Rfd8
18. Rd1{ I will end my coverage here. My computer swears this position is equal after a move like ... Rd6 , which doesn't seem to do much. I'm sure Black must be fine, but it seems hard for him to play with two pawns less and no direct route to make any threats. Plus, they have to get here, knowing an early novelty over half the game ago and a bunch of perfect moves afterward. }
