16. Bg4( 16...f5? { I could easily see a human doing this. }17.d3!± { Black's center is collapsing immediately. The machine wants to castle and let White take a healthy pawn on  e4 . } )
17. f3
17. exf3
18. Nxf3
18. b5( { This is a very hard move for a human to find. It looks like it is begging for a disaster on the long diagonal, but Black can just barely hold the position together. }18...O-O 19.Rxb7 { A pawn is a pawn. } )
19. Nxd4
19. Qxd4+
20. e3
20. Qd7( 20...Bxd1? 21.exd4 { Black has too much hanging stuff and White wins material. } )
21. Qb3{ Black cannot castle, his rook is loose on  a8 , and his pawn is loose on  b5 . It almost feels like an insult to chess that he is not busted! }
21. Ra5{ This is a very awkward-looking and difficult move to play for Black. I would think  Rb8  is much more natural. }( 21...Rb8? { This feels the most human to me. }22.Bd5! { Black's king is frozen in the center and he will soon face a vicious attack when White's pieces come into play. } )
22. Bd5
22. b4{ The point of putting the rook on  a5  is revealed - he can pressure our  d5 -bishop. }
23. e4
23. Bc5+
24. Kh1
24. h5{ Black is getting some counterplay. My computer, in its infinite wisdom, claims this position is equal. It just looks messy to me, and in practice, I'd still take White. }
25. Bb2
25. h4
26. Rbe1{ Not very subtle.  e4 - e5  is coming. Stockfish is giving zeroes, and you'll never win this position in correspondence chess. But in human play, I think the position is still very rich, and it took quite a lot of effort for Black to make it here. }
