[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) 2...Nf6 3.Bg2 d5 with 6...Nc7"]
[Black "4...Nxd5 5.Nf3 Nc6 with 6...Nc7 and 7...e5 #16"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c5
2. g3
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. d5{ One of the most direct things Black can do is to try to take as big a share of the center as possible, and quickly pushing  d7 - d5  is a very natural way to try to make this happen. }
4. cxd5{ Of course we take on  d5 . }
4. Nxd5
5. Nf3
5. Nc6{ Nothing else makes any sense. Now, I think we should challenge the  d5 -knight immediately. }
6. Nc3{ Now, Black's two main moves here, by far, are  g6  and  Nc7 , both of which give him very good chances to fight for equality. But he has some extraneous options we should also be ready for. }
6. Nc7{ For a long time, this was considered to be Black's big main move. It makes a lot of sense - he gets his knight off the loose square, does not allow us to capture towards the center, and he is ready for  e7 - e5  next. Fundamentally, his position is quite good, and we should be very direct to pressure his space advantage before he can consolidate and just be better. }
7. a3{ I like this move a lot. White can afford to waste no time, and not so subtly advertises his intentions to attack Black's space advantage directly with  b2 - b4  next. }
7. e5{ This would be the consistent follow-up, and it is best against 7.  O-O , which is White's main move. Indeed, it is Black's most common move by a wide margin, though I think  g7 - g6  is stronger. Here, White is able to get his desired break-in. }
8. b4
8. f6{ Once Black has committed to  e7 - e5 , this is his main move. He bolsters his  e5 -pawn, and hopes to take back on  c5  with the bishop in one move if we were to capture. It's logical enough, but I still think White can apply some pressure to Black's position if he is a little patient. }
9. Rb1{ I like this move a lot. White brings his rook to the b-file, which will surely open someday, and makes sure that Black still cannot comfortably take on  b4 . }
9. Bf5{ This should be Black's best move. He develops a new piece with a gain of tempo, and the generally desirable move  d2 - d3  would fail to  cxb4 , when the knight hanging on  c3  with check means the tactics will not favor us. }
10. b5{  Rb1 - b2  is playable as well, but a bit less adventurous. }
10. Nd4
11. d3{ White is ready for  Nd2  next, with good pressure on the long diagonal, and eventually, the  d4 -knight will be awkward in face of the threat of  e2 - e3 . I don't believe Black brings the bishop to  f5  and does not take on  b1  when he has the chance, though it has to be said that he chose 10...  Nd4  in the only human game to reach this position. }
