3. d5{ One of the most direct things Black can do is to try to take as big a share of the center as possible, and quickly pushing  d7 - d5  is a very natural way to try to make this happen. }
4. cxd5{ Of course we take on  d5 . }
4. Nxd5
5. Nf3
5. Nc6{ Nothing else makes any sense. Now, I think we should challenge the  d5 -knight immediately. }
6. Nc3{ Now, Black's two main moves here, by far, are  g6  and  Nc7 , both of which give him very good chances to fight for equality. But he has some extraneous options we should also be ready for. }
6. Nc7{ For a long time, this was considered to be Black's big main move. It makes a lot of sense - he gets his knight off the loose square, does not allow us to capture towards the center, and he is ready for  e7 - e5  next. Fundamentally, his position is quite good, and we should be very direct to pressure his space advantage before he can consolidate and just be better. }
7. a3{ I like this move a lot. White can afford to waste no time, and not so subtly advertises his intentions to attack Black's space advantage directly with  b2 - b4  next. }
7. g6{ This is Black's best move. It is not an easy one to make, since he could have just as easily done it on the previous move, and historically,  Nd5 - c7  has always been played with the intention of advancing  e7 - e5  next. With  g6 , Black is arguing that our move  a2 - a3  is not great because the hope of later following up with  b2 - b4  is less enticing when Black's bishop on  b7  will exert pressure along the long diagonal. }
8. h4{ I like immediately trying to take advantage of the  g7 - g6  advance. The positions start to become irrational very quickly, but this is exactly what we want against guys who open the game with 1...  c5 ! They usually make this move with the hopes of keeping things more quiet and more symmetrical. }
8. h6{ Historically, this has been Black's most common move. It certainly feels like a very human reaction - Black makes sure that he can always meet  h4 - h5  with  g6 - g5 . But in my opinion, this is not best, and White has a very nice idea available to him. }
9. Na4{ This move is technically a novelty, but since the computer offers it, I don't think it should be considered too groundbreaking. It is simple and direct - White hits the  c5 -pawn, and Black does not have a great way to defend it. }
9. Qd6{ This seems pretty natural to me. }
10. b4{ Again, this move proves powerful. }
10. cxb4
11. Bb2
11. e5( { A sad necessity. }11...Rg8 12.axb4± { White has the world's best reversed Benko Gambit. Black's king will be stuck in the center forever, and White should easily win the game on the queenside. The machine claims Black is dead lost, and I don't feel a need to argue with it here. } )
12. axb4{ White takes back his pawn, and Black cannot take again on  b4  thanks to his  e5 -pawn hanging. It feels like White should be much better, but sadly, despite Black's weird-looking play and the positive flow of the game for us in the last few moves, the machine claims only a small edge. }
12. Bg7( 12...Qxb4? 13.Nxe5! { Black loses the house. My computer gives +5! } )
13. Nc3{ I like this move, forcing Black to go pawn-grabbing.  b4 - b5  is a serious threat. }
13. Nxb4( 13...O-O? 14.b5!± { Black's knight is kicked away and  Bb2 - a3  is a big problem. Black is in trouble. } )
14. Ne4
14. Qe7
15. Ra5
15. O-O( { This is sadly necessary for Black.    • }15...Nc6? { I could easily see a human making this move. }16.Ba3! { Black will not survive a check on  d6  coming next. } )( { • }15...f5? { This gets brutalized by checks and captures all the way through. }16.Nxe5! fxe4 17.Nxg6! { Let the bodies hit the floor! }17...Qd7 18.Bxg7 Qxg7 19.Nxh8 Qxh8 20.Qa4+ Nc6 21.Qxe4++- { Black's king is ridiculous, and his position is coming under pressure from so many angles all at once. } )
16. Rxe5
16. Be6( 16...Bxe5?! 17.Nxe5 { and after, for example, }17...Bf5 18.h5 { Black's king position is shaky. } )
17. O-O{ White is ready for  Qd1 - a1  next, putting more pressure on the long diagonal. Black has a lot of problems to solve here, and taking on  e5  will only ever add to his woes. }
