7. g6{ This is Black's best move. It is not an easy one to make, since he could have just as easily done it on the previous move, and historically,  Nd5 - c7  has always been played with the intention of advancing  e7 - e5  next. With  g6 , Black is arguing that our move  a2 - a3  is not great because the hope of later following up with  b2 - b4  is less enticing when Black's bishop on  b7  will exert pressure along the long diagonal. }
8. h4{ I like immediately trying to take advantage of the  g7 - g6  advance. The positions start to become irrational very quickly, but this is exactly what we want against guys who open the game with 1...  c5 ! They usually make this move with the hopes of keeping things more quiet and more symmetrical. }
8. Bg4{ This move is not too common, but I definitely think it is best. Black develops a new piece and prevents  h4 - h5 . }
9. Qb3{ Now we are in fresh territory. White hits the  b7 -pawn. }
9. Rb8{ This feels like the most natural move to me, and the one I would probably expect a human to play. It's quite nice that it leaves Black in trouble! }
10. Ng5{ As it turns out, defending against the threat on  f7  is not trivial. }
10. Be6( { This is Black's best move, and not an easy one for a human. Nobody wants to give up a bishop like this voluntarily. }10...e6? 11.Qa4+- { Just like that, Black is busted. His bishop is just about trapped. } )
11. Nxe6
11. Nxe6
12. h5{ White is a bit better thanks to his strong bishop on  g2 , and Black will struggle to castle since he doesn't really want to put his king right in the line of fire. White can retreat his queen back to  d1  and complete his development with  b3  and  Bb2 , and Black's position looks very suspect to me. }
