6. Nc7{ For a long time, this was considered to be Black's big main move. It makes a lot of sense - he gets his knight off the loose square, does not allow us to capture towards the center, and he is ready for  e7 - e5  next. Fundamentally, his position is quite good, and we should be very direct to pressure his space advantage before he can consolidate and just be better. }
7. a3{ I like this move a lot. White can afford to waste no time, and not so subtly advertises his intentions to attack Black's space advantage directly with  b2 - b4  next. }
7. g6{ This is Black's best move. It is not an easy one to make, since he could have just as easily done it on the previous move, and historically,  Nd5 - c7  has always been played with the intention of advancing  e7 - e5  next. With  g6 , Black is arguing that our move  a2 - a3  is not great because the hope of later following up with  b2 - b4  is less enticing when Black's bishop on  g7  will exert pressure along the long diagonal. }
8. h4{ I like immediately trying to take advantage of the  g7 - g6  advance. The positions start to become irrational very quickly, but this is exactly what we want against guys who open the game with 1...  c5 ! They usually make this move with the hopes of keeping things more quiet and more symmetrical. }
8. h5{ Of course, Black could respond in kind with  h7 - h5 , stopping us from gaining any further space. But this weakens the  g5 -square, and it feels weird to me- the machine thinks it is a decent enough move, but Black has almost never chosen it in human practice. }
9. Ne4
9. b6{ This feels like the most human move to me, but it does not equalize. }
10. Nfg5{ White takes advantage of the weakened  g5 -square and makes the threat of a discovery on the long diagonal. }
10. Bb7{ This feels like a very human move to me, and I would honestly expect even a very strong player to make it. }
11. Nxc5
11. bxc5
12. Qb3{ This somewhat surprising tactic wins a clean pawn and ruins Black's position as well. It's all over. }
