[White "5) 2...Nf6 3.Bg2 g6"]
[Black "4...Bg7 5.d4 cxd4 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c5
2. g3
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. g6{ It might look like Black is aiming to transpose into some kind of mainline Symmetrical English as we will see later on, but in fact, the knight already being on  f6  changes the character of the position a lot. White should end up better if Black develops with ... Bg7  and ... Nc6 . Black can instead try to delay ... Nc6  and aim to play some kind of King's Indian with an early ... c5 . }
4. Nf3
4. Bg7{ Now, it is very important that White instigate a fight in the center immediately, and not wait around with castling. }
5. d4( { This is the right time for  d2 - d4 . }5.O-O?! O-O 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 d5! { I believe Black is fine here. The point is that after }8.Nc3 dxc4! { White is missing a check on  a4 . } )
5. cxd4
6. Nxd4
6. O-O( 6...Nc6 7.Nc3 { Transposes to the 5...  Nf6   chapter.  } )
7. Nc2{ This rare move was tried against me by Rinat Jumabayev at   the last World Cup , and to great effect. I ended up winning the game, but Black surely is not equalizing here. We will see how he could have played better in the annotated games section. The point is that White is preventing Black from pushing  d7 - d5  without walking into any tricks. }( 7.Nc3 { looks more natural, but after }7...Qc7! 8.b3 d5! { Black has a reasonable counterplay. } )
7. Qc7{ This would be the typical move for Black against 7.  Nc3  instead, but now we see a point in playing  Nc2 . }
8. Ne3{ White is able to protect his  c4 -pawn without pushing  b2 - b3  and asking for trouble on the long diagonal. Next up is  O-O ,  Nb1 - c3 , and eventually  b2 - b3  when he is ready.  Bc1 - b2  will follow, and White has a pleasant space advantage. }
8. d6
9. Nc3
9. Nc6
10. O-O
10. Be6
11. Rb1{ I like this final preparatory move. White is ready for  b3  and  Bb2  next, with a nice space advantage. }
