11. Qxd8+{ I quite like this enterprising queen sacrifice. }
11. Qxd8
12. Bxc3{ At stupid high depths, my computer insists that this position is absolutely equal. 0.00 after the top few moves for either side for the next. In a higher chess sense, it may well be right. But from a human perspective, I think White's play is much easier.     He will castle, and bring his rooks to the center, and his position is void of weaknesses. The main strength that a queen has over smaller pieces is that her versatility allows her to attack lots of things at once, which her opponent will struggle to defend. Here, White's position is totally void of any weakness Black can feasibly target! By contrast, the main strength of a higher quantity of smaller pieces is that they can all focus on one target.     Here, White has a simple plan. Castle, rooks to  d1  and  c1 , and eventually push through with  b2 - b4 - b5 , gaining space and making a passed queenside pawn. We will see  a game  in the illustrative games section where White wins very cleanly in one of the only classical games to ever reach this position. }
