14. Re8{ I could very easily see a human make this move. It looks so natural and it is very hard to find a position in any kind of Benoni where  Rf8 - e8  is a huge mistake, but here it is. This highlights how dangerous Black's position can be to a human. }
15. Qa1{ All of a sudden, Black is facing a massive problem with  Nc3 - e4  coming next. He is already getting into serious trouble. }
15. Ng4{ This would have been Black's saving grace if he had correctly played  Qd8 - e7  instead of  Rf8 - e8 . Now, Black loses. }
16. h3
16. Ne5
17. Nce4{ Since Black did not play  Qd8 - e7 , his  d6 -pawn is loose. As such, with both  Nxd6  and  f4  threatened, Black is losing heavy material on the spot. }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 2...Nf6 3.Bg2 g6"]
[Black "4...Bg7 5.d4 O-O #8"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c5
2. g3
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. g6{ It might look like Black is aiming to transpose into some kind of mainline Symmetrical English as we will see later on, but in fact, the knight already being on  f6  changes the character of the position a lot. White should end up better if Black develops with ... Bg7  and ... Nc6 . Black can instead try to delay ... Nc6  and aim to play some kind of King's Indian with an early ... c5 . }
4. Nf3
4. Bg7{ Now, it is very important that White instigate a fight in the center immediately, and not wait around with castling. }
5. d4( { This is the right time for  d2 - d4 . }5.O-O?! O-O 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 d5! { I believe Black is fine here. The point is that after }8.Nc3 dxc4! { White is missing a check on  a4 . } )
5. O-O{ This is actually quite an annoying move order. In Part I, I found an early  h2 - h3 , delaying  Ng1 - f3 , against the King's Indian plans with the specific intention of avoiding the ... c5  line. I had not anticipated that with Black's present move order, he can get this line and we cannot avoid it! In general, I think this is extremely unlikely to happen. I think the biggest appeal of the King's Indian is how impervious it is to move-order tricks, and that Black can go ... Nf6 , ... g6 , ... Bg7 , ... d6 , and ... O-O  against anything White does, and he totally does not care what we are up to.     It seems like a huge stretch to me that someone would decide to play the King's Indian, an objectively suspicious opening aimed at getting good practical chances, and decide specifically to want to play a less common idea against the Fianchetto System that usually results in symmetry, and then be so adamant that they want this system and only this system that they learn an entire 1...  c5  repertoire where White has tons of options apart from 2.  g3 , just so that they can avoid my 6.  h3  idea in the normal move order. Still, at a high enough level, I suppose this could happen, and we should be ready. }
6. Nc3
6. d6( 6...d5 7.dxc5 { Transposes to the 5...  d5   lines.  }7...Nc6 7.O-O { Black has nothing better than  d7 - d6 , transposing to the mainline, or ... c5xd4 , transposing to the mainline Symmetrical English lines seen later on. } )
7. O-O
7. Nc6{ By transposition, we have ended up playing against Gawain Jones' main recommendation in his King's Indian course here on Chessable. For the most part, I think his coverage of the Fianchetto system was pretty decent, so much so that I was trying to use a move order trick to try to avoid some of his pawn tries. Upon the realization that I was going to have to go into this line anyway if Black is extremely well-tuned to our move order and even learns an entirely separate repertoire from move 1 in order to reach these positions, I took a closer look, and found a line where I believe Jones somewhat underappreciates the strategic danger in Black's position. }( 7...cxd4 8.Nxd4⩲ { White is better with his extra space, and Black's best move is  Nb8 - c6 , transposing to the ... Nf6   lines  in the mainline Symmetrical English. } )
8. d5{ I am not interested in symmetry here. }
8. Na5
9. Nd2
9. e6( 9...Rb8 10.Rb1! { Black has nothing better than  a7 - a6 , transposing to the 9...  a6   analysis.  } )
10. Rb1{ I like getting the rook off the long diagonal. Our hope is to neutralize the  g7 -bishop with  Bc1 - b2 . }
10. exd5{ I struggle to imagine anything else. }
11. cxd5{ Next up is  b2 - b4 , a typical break that White can fight for in the Benoni. He will break down Black's space advantage from the  c5 -pawn and get ready to bring his own bishop to  b2 . }
11. Bd7{ Still following Jones' mainline. }
12. b4
12. cxb4
13. Rxb4
13. Rc8{ Jones ends his coverage here, claiming Black is fine with counterplay on the c-file. I certainly could not bust this line or anything like that, and I do believe Black is more or less okay if he really knows what he is doing, but I think his position is actually very dangerous strategically. }
14. Bb2{ White has a very blunt plan coming in the next couple moves.  Qd1 - a1 ,  Nc3 - e4 , and smash the long diagonal. Black has to be very precise to hang on. }
14. Re8{ I could very easily see a human make this move. It looks so natural and it is very hard to find a position in any kind of Benoni where  Rf8 - e8  is a huge mistake, but here it is. This highlights how dangerous Black's position can be to a human. }
15. Qa1{ All of a sudden, Black is facing a massive problem with  Nc3 - e4  coming next. He is already getting into serious trouble. }
15. Bf5{ This is Black's only move to even keep the game going. }
16. Nce4
16. Nxe4{ Now things get forced. }
17. Bxe4
17. Bxe4
18. Bxg7
18. Bxd5
19. Bh8{ With an obvious threat, so Black has only one move. }
19. f6
20. Bxf6{ Black will face long term problems with his king safety and the weak  d6 -pawn, but at least he isn't immediately done for. }
