6. a3{ I like this move a lot. White is hoping to quickly aim for queenside expansion with  b2 - b4 , taking advantage of Black blunting his own bishop on  g7 . We see this theme a lot in other lines as well- when Black tries to take a lot of space in the center while falling behind in development,  a2 - a3  and  b2 - b4  is a good way to try to put him under pressure. }
6. Nge7{ In my opinion, this is Black's best move. Once he has played  e7 - e5 , he should know that the knight will want to go to  e7 . But, he is not yet sure whether his pawn should go to  d6  or  d5 . Now, if we continue to push for  b2 - b4 , Black will potentially be able to hit us with  d7 - d5  in one move, striking back in the center. Some care must be taken. }
7. d3{ This serves as important prophylaxis against  d7 - d5 . }
7. d6
8. Rb1{ This is the easiest way to keep the repertoire consistent. }
8. a5{ Now, sadly we cannot play the  Nf3 - d2 - f1 - e3  maneuvre so easily. Black, having spared a tempo on castling, would be able to play  Bc8 - e6  and  d7 - d5  before we could stop him. }
9. O-O( 9.Nd2?! Be6! { Black will execute the  d6 - d5  break before we can bring the knight to  e3 . } )
9. O-O
10. Ne1{ This is a more traditional plan against the Botvinnik setup than I would normally like to play, but I think the inclusion of  a2 - a3  and  a7 - a5  is notably in White's favor, and Black has lost out on some options that he would have if we choose this way of playing agaisnt anything he might try. }
10. Be6{ Nothing else makes any sense. Black needs to be ready for the  d6 - d5  advance before our knight reaches  e3 . }
11. Bg5{ I like this move a lot. White makes sure Black cannot push  d6 - d5 . }
11. f6{ Black really needs to make this move to get the  d6 - d5  break through at all costs. However, this shuts down his bishop. }
12. Be3{ White hits the  c5 -pawn, stopping  d6 - d5  once move. }
12. f5( 12...b6 13.Nd5!⩲ { White prevents  d6 - d5  and can look for  b2 - b4  to come next. } )
13. Bg5{ Back we go! }
13. Qd7( 13...h6? 14.Bxe7! { Again, this should be nice for White. Black has to either give up the  b7 -pawn or surrender control of the  d5 -square. } )
14. Nc2{ Now, Black is forced into action directly. He certainly cannot allow our  c2 -knight to go to  e3  and  d5 . He must either execute the  d6 - d5  break right now, or restrict our knight with  f5 - f4 . }
14. f4{ This does stop the knight from coming to  e3 , but it is a very committal move as well. }
15. Nd5
15. Rae8
16. b4{ White's queenside play looks very promising to me. }
16. Nf5{ My computer offers this move as best, surrendering the  d5 -square permanently but hoping to get counterplay with  h7 - h6  coming next. }
17. gxf4{ White jumps into action. }
17. h6( { This feels like Black's most consistent move to me. }17...axb4 { exchanging a-pawn is also possible, but it should not change the position much. }18.axb4 { Black really should push  h7 - h6  anyway. 18... h6  19.e4! } )
18. e4
18. Nfd4{ This feels most human to me. }
19. f5
19. hxg5{ I could easily see a human making this move, but it is a positional blunder. }
20. fxe6
20. Nxe6( 20...Rxe6 21.b5! { Next up is  Nxd4  and  Bh3 , and White wins an exchange. } )
21. Bh3{ Black will have a hard time dealing with the pin, and he will be ultimately be left with a bad bishop against a good knight. White is much better. }
