6. a3{ I like this move a lot. White is hoping to quickly aim for queenside expansion with  b2 - b4 , taking advantage of Black blunting his own bishop on  g7 . We see this theme a lot in other lines as well- when Black tries to take a lot of space in the center while falling behind in development,  a2 - a3  and  b2 - b4  is a good way to try to put him under pressure. }
6. Nge7{ In my opinion, this is Black's best move. Once he has played  e7 - e5 , he should know that the knight will want to go to  e7 . But, he is not yet sure whether his pawn should go to  d6  or  d5 . Now, if we continue to push for  b2 - b4 , Black will potentially be able to hit us with  d7 - d5  in one move, striking back in the center. Some care must be taken. }
7. d3{ This serves as important prophylaxis against  d7 - d5 . }
7. O-O{ This should be best. Black makes another move he knows he has to, and remains flexible on what to do with his d-pawn. But, now we can deny him the option of  d7 - d5 . }
8. Nd2{ I like this plan a lot. White regroups the knight to  e3 . }
8. d6{ Now, before we continue the knight regrouping, it is important to provoke Black into playing  a7 - a5 . }
9. Rb1{ Not especially subtle. We want  b2 - b4 . }
9. a5
10. Nf1{ Now and only now, we go for this regrouping. }
10. Be6
11. Ne3
11. Rb8
12. Ned5{ Since we managed to convince Black to push  a7 - a5 , he is missing the plan of  a7 - a6  and  b7 - b5  to try to pressure our center from the side. As such, he doesn't have a great way to contest White's activity. Our plan for the future should be to castle, play  Bc1 - d2 , and push for  b2 - b4 . }
