5. e6{ From a strategic point of view, I think this is Black's most ambitious move and his most direct chance to fight for equality. The best setup Black can hope to achieve is ... e6 , ... Nge7 , and ... O-O , and then he can remain flexible with his d-pawn, aiming to either go to  d6  or  d5  depending on how we proceed. Indeed, if White were to simply castle here, Black would get exactly what he wants. We should be very direct to try to make him uncomfortable. }
6. d4{ This move can hardly be considered a surprise, as it has been well known to be White's most challenging option for many years. We aim to blow up the center while Black is lagging behind in development. Now, Black can take on  d4  with either the knight or the pawn, and we need to be ready for both options. }
6. cxd4{ This is the old main move, and in my opinion, a very reasonable chance to fight for equality. I have played this position myself from the black side more than once. }
7. Nb5{ Black should be careful not to allow a check on  d6 . }
7. d5
8. cxd5{ Now, once upon a time, checking on  a5  was thought to be Black's best move. It is not that easy to deal with and remains a viable attempt to fight for equality, but I think ... exd5  should be considered the main move. }
8. exd5{ I would consider this the main line nowadays. Black accepts an isolated pawn, and claims that we will lose enough time with  Nb1 - c3 - b5 - xd4  that he should be okay. It is not so stupid, and I have played this way with Black myself, but I still think we can put his position under some pressure. }
9. O-O
9. Nf6{ Until recently, it was sort of taken for granted that Black would put the knight on  e7 , which felt like a more natural square. Nowadays, the machines do not show a huge preference as to where the knight should go, and Peter Svidler even recommended this move here on Chessable. }
10. Nbxd4{ It's important to remember that we have to take with different knights depending on whether Black develops with  Ng8 - f6  or  Ng8 - e7 . Here, we take back with the b-knight. }
10. O-O{ Now, I like an interesting move that Svidler does not mention, trying to take advantage of Black's knight on  f6  clogging the long diagonal. }
11. b3{ The machine is not that impressed with this move, but I think it is a very decent human attempt to fight for an edge. One point that I really like is that Black's best response is to play  Nc6xd4 , which is not an easy move for a human to choose. The conventional wisdom in IQP (Isolated Queen's Pawn) positions is that the side with the isolani does not want to exchange minor pieces. }
11. Re8{ This feels like the sort of automatic move to me. I think it is a strategic inaccuracy. }
12. Bb2{ Now, the problem Black faces is that if he ever takes on  d4 , we will be very happy to take back with the bishop. Next up should be  Nd4xc6 , and I like our chances to play against the hanging pawns. }
12. Bg4{ This feels like a very human move to me. }
13. Nxc6
13. bxc6
14. Ne5{ White will trade some minor pieces and simplify the position to get good play against the hanging pawns. }
