6. d4{ This move can hardly be considered a surprise, as it has been well known to be White's most challenging option for many years. We aim to blow up the center while Black is lagging behind in development. Now, Black can take on  d4  with either the knight or the pawn, and we need to be ready for both options. }
6. cxd4{ This is the old main move, and in my opinion, a very reasonable chance to fight for equality. I have played this position myself from the black side more than once. }
7. Nb5{ Black should be careful not to allow a check on  d6 . }
7. d5
8. cxd5{ Now, once upon a time, checking on  a5  was thought to be Black's best move. It is not that easy to deal with and remains a viable attempt to fight for equality, but I think ... exd5  should be considered the main move. }
8. exd5{ I would consider this the main line nowadays. Black accepts an isolated pawn, and claims that we will lose enough time with  Nb1 - c3 - b5 - xd4  that he should be okay. It is not so stupid, and I have played this way with Black myself, but I still think we can put his position under some pressure. }
9. O-O
9. Nge7{ This has always been considered the main move. }
10. Nfxd4{ I remembered being very happy with myself for finding this idea many years ago, but now the machines shoot it out instantly. White's reason is that he wants his bishop on  e3  to support the  d4 -knight and then his other knight can always come back to  c3  if ever harassed, pressuring the  d5 -pawn. This is all made possible by Black's knight on  e7  rather than  f6  - we do not need to fear any  Nf6 - g4  jumps, and  Re8xe3  is not a thing. }
10. a6{ This is also possible, forcing us to change the structure with  Nxc6 . But, I am quite happy to play against the hanging pawns. }
11. Nxc6
11. bxc6
12. Nc3
12. O-O
13. Na4{ White has easy play with  Bd2  and  Rc1  coming next. He looks pleasantly better to me.  a7 - a6  is really out of place, weakening the  b6 -square and denying the  b8 -bishop a good home. }
