14. dxc5
15. Rc2{ Now, we reach another position that I think only a computer could be stupid enough to call equal. Ask the machine and it will insist Black's position is totally fine. In human terms, we are playing  Ne4  next and taking on  c5 , leaving Black with a crippled queenside structure. Someday, this may well matter. I would think in a game between beings of flesh and blood, White has to be favored.     All throughout this course, from the Tarrasch to the 6...  Nh6  symmetrical English to the 5...  e6  Fischer system, I found myself very surprised with how comfortable the machine is accepting an isolated pawn without any attacking chances or counterplay. Perhaps this only highlights a shortcoming of my own understanding, but I think in human terms, isolated pawns should count. }
