5. Nf3( { Finally, it is time to start coverage of the mainline Symmetrical English! This position can be reached by a number of move orders, and seems very likely to arise after the game begins with   }1.c4 c5 2.g3 { . } )
5. d6
6. O-O{ In modern times, Black's main move has emerged to be  e7 - e6 . But he has a lot of other options in this position! }
6. Bg4{ This move is pretty simple in its nature. Black voluntarily parts with his bishop pair, and claims that this will be the only imbalance in the position that favors us. He will get his knight to its best square on  e7  without any issue, and we definitely will not manage to push  d2 - d4 . It is not such a bad line, and the only one within the ' Silly Sidelines ' section that potentially has a valid gripe with my chosen nomenclature. Still, it is not easy to convince me that White isn't a little better when he can grab the bishop pair so early. }( 6...e5 7.a3 { transposes to the 5...  e5  lines. } )
7. h3
7. Bxf3
8. Bxf3
8. e6
9. Bg2{ There is no particular need to play this move now, but we certainly will have to at some point if Black ever attacks the bishop with  Nc6 - d4  or if he ever plays ... e5  and ... Qd7  to hit  h3 . I figure we might as well get that out of the way right now. }
9. Nge7{ At this point, it should be pretty clear that we will not be able to advance  d2 - d4 . So, we should aim to put Black's position under pressure by aiming for a  b2 - b4  advance instead. }
10. a3( 10.Rb1 { This move order is fine too. } )
10. O-O
11. Rb1{ Our last couple of moves have been anything but subtle. Black now has to decide what to do about  b2 - b4 . }
11. Qd7{ Ignoring the advance is not ridiculous, but it is something I generally would be happy to see. }
12. b4{ Of course. }
12. Rac8{ Black's position remains very solid, and it is not too easy to make further progress. We start by getting the bishop to the long diagonal. }
13. Bb2{ This move does involve offering a pawn, but I think Black is best advised not to take it. }
13. cxb4{ I could easily see a human grabbing  b4  here. }
14. axb4
14. Nxb4{ Now, we have to remember an important move. }
15. Ba3{ The knight is hit, and Black's position is rife with weaknesses. We have a lot of threats. }
15. Bxc3
16. dxc3
16. Nbc6
17. Qxd6
17. Qxd6
18. Bxd6{ White should be a bit better here as well. The active bishops look really nice and I can't imagine the pawn structure will hurt us much. Black will probably have to advance  b7 - b6  at some point to avoid losing the  b7 -pawn, and then we can always liquidate one of the doubled pawns with  c4 - c5  next. }
