8. Bd7{ Black takes advantage of having already played  d7 - d6 , which was not such an easy move to accomplish back in the 5...  Nf6   section . This is not such a dumb setup, and it is one that I have used more than once with Black, and with reasonable results. Still, in modern times, I think White can show an edge. }
9. Nc2{ I think this move makes a lot of sense, and it is very consistent with what we saw in the 5th move sidelines section. White avoids exchanging pieces and gets the knight off the loose square. The plan in the coming moves should be  b2 - b3 ,  Bc1 - b2 ,  e2 - e4  to gain more space. }
9. Qc8{ It makes some sense to immediately go after the bishop on  g2 . Anyone who has ever played the white side of the Dragon knows that getting the bishop to  h6  as a prelude to an  h2 - h4  advance makes it impossible for Black to hope to keep the kingside closed with  h7 - h5 . There are some obvious parallels here, but I don't think we need to worry too much about getting mated. }
10. b3
10. Bh3( 10...h5 11.h4 { Transposes to the 9...  h5  line. } )
11. Bb2{ Now, my computer thinks Black should castle, which reaches a similar position to what we would see after 9...  O-O . }
11. h5{ This is the only move I would be worried about. Indeed, it looks scary-  h5 - h4  comes next, and if we are not careful, we can be mated before we know it. Luckily, flank attacks against the king rarely work in open positions if the defending side has more pawns in the center, and this position is no exception. }( 11...O-O 12.f3 { White is ready for  e4 ,  Qe2 , rooks to  d1  and  c1 , and knight to  e3 . He should be better thanks to the extra space. } )
12. f3{ White makes sure that he is always ready to meet  h5 - h4  with  g3 - g4 , and I think Black's attack is out of steam. We will continue with what should be a familiar setup by this point,  e2 - e4 ,  Qd1 - e2 , and rooks to  d1  and  c1 . }
