3. Bg7
4. Nc3
4. Nc6
5. Nf3( { Finally, it is time to start coverage of the mainline Symmetrical English! This position can be reached by a number of move orders, and seems very likely to arise after the game begins with   }1.c4 c5 2.g3 { . } )
5. d6
6. O-O
6. Nf6{ This move might look similar to 5...  Nf6 , but in reality it is quite different. We get the  d2 - d4  advance in all the same, but now Black is able to get his bishop to  d7 . }
7. d4
7. cxd4
8. Nxd4
8. Bd7{ Black takes advantage of having already played  d7 - d6 , which was not such an easy move to accomplish back in the 5...  Nf6   section . This is not such a dumb setup, and it is one that I have used more than once with Black, and with reasonable results. Still, in modern times, I think White can show an edge. }
9. Nc2{ I think this move makes a lot of sense, and it is very consistent with what we saw in the 5th move sidelines section. White avoids exchanging pieces and gets the knight off the loose square. The plan in the coming moves should be  b2 - b3 ,  Bc1 - b2 ,  e2 - e4  to gain more space. }
9. h5{ This feels like Black's best move to me. It is not particularly subtle, he wants to push  h5 - h4  next, and unfortunately for us,  h2 - h3  fails for tactical reasons. We have to push the pawn to  h4 . }
10. h4( { This weakens the  g4 -square. Black's knight could become very annoying if we are not careful, but I think White has it under control. }10.h3?! { This is a more typical way of trying to preserve the kingside, but here it fails tactically. }10...Qc8! { White's king is provoked to  h2 . He should push  h3 - h4  and lose a tempo, but let's see what happens if we remain oblivious. }11.Kh2 Na5! 12.b3 { And now a problem... }12...Ng4+! { Black wins material. } )
10. Qc8
11. b3
11. Nh7{ This would be the only way Black could play that would scare me. He opens up a threat to the  c3 -knight and points out that it is not so easy to prevent its capture while simultaneously avoiding  g6 - g5  opening the kingside. Care must be taken. }
12. Qd3{ A very important move. White defends the  c3 -knight while still keeping an eye on  g5 , and invites Black's knight to  e5 . }( { • }12.Bb2? { This looks automatic but would play right into Black's hands. }12...g5! { This could get very scary very fast. } )( { • }12.Qd2 g5! 13.hxg5 Nxg5! { Since Black's knight was not provoked to  e5 , this move becomes possible. This looks very scary for White to me.  Ng5 - h3  and  h5 - h4  is coming next. } )
12. Ne5
13. Qd2{ Now and only now, White brings his queen back to  d2 . }
13. g5
14. hxg5{ And we see that Black cannot take on  g5 . The knight on  e5  would be in the way of his ability to capture  c3 . }
14. h4( { This looks quite intimidating, but it is time to take the fight to Black. The center is open after all. }14...Nxg5? 15.Qxg5+- { Black is missing  Bg7xc3 . } )
15. f4
15. Ng6
16. Bb2
16. hxg3
17. Ne3{ White is ready for  Nc3 - e4  to come next. The position is very sharp by the standards of the Symmetrical English, but I find White's initiative to be more promising than Black's. The computer confirms we have a slight edge here. }
