13. Qxc3
13. Qc7{ Black's point is revealed. By exchanging off the  c3 -knight, his queen has access to the  c7 -square without being hit by  Nc3 - d5 . It seems like Black should not be in such bad shape - he can aim for  Bc8 - c6  next, perhaps put his rooks on  c8  and  b8 , and eventually ... b5  will come. It doesn't seem unreasonable to think he should be okay with a bit less space when some pieces have been exchanged and he does have an active plan to break down the space advantage at the source. But watch what happens next. }
14. b3
14. Be6
15. Qe3{ One of the biggest assets of having a space advantage is that you will have a much easier time switching from one side of the board to the other than your opponent will. Seemingly out of nowhere, Black could face mating threats with  Rd1 - d4 - h4  and  Qe3 - h6 . }
15. a5( 15...a6 { My computer prefers this move. Still, after }16.Rd4 Kg7! 17.Rad1 { Black's position is no bed of roses. The rook can come to  h4  whenever it wants to. For example, after }17...Rab8 18.Rh4! Rh8 19.Qh6+ Kg8 { Black surely will not be mated directly, but he is stuck with a passive rook in the corner. Does he really want to push ... b5 , allowing the c-file to open while he has a heave piece out of play? }20.Bd5 Bxd5 21.cxd5 { White will take the c-file first and Black is in big trouble. } )
16. Rd4
