10. b5( 10...Rb8 { This was definitely the stronger move, though I would prefer White all the same and the machine does give him a slight edge. } )
11. cxb5
11. axb5
12. Nxb5
12. Qa5
13. Nc3{ The difference between this position and a normal Benko gambit is that White's d-pawn is back on  d3  rather than  d5 . As a result, his  g2 -bishop is not blocked, he has the potential plan to clog the long diagonal with a well timed  d3 - d4 , and Black is missing the  c5 - c4  resource to open the b-file. }
13. Rab8( 13...Rfb8 { This looks more consistent with the Benko Gambit to me, though still after }14.Rfc1 { with  b2 - b3  coming next and eventually a well-timed  d3 - d4 , White should be clearly better. } )
14. Rfc1{ Magnus has always been amazing at coordinating his pieces. He overprotects the  c3  knight so that he can safely play  b2 - b3  and then  Be3 - h6  without hanging it. }
14. Rfc8
15. b3
15. e5
16. Bh6
16. Nd4( 16...Bh8 { There is not a ton of sense in saving the bishop if it is blocked in by the  e5 -pawn. }17.Ng5! { White is ready for  Nge4  next, and Black is totally without counterplay. } )
17. Bxg7
17. Nxf3+( 17...Kxg7 { This may have been a better choice, but after }18.Nxd4 exd4 19.Ne4± { Black's position still looks awful to me. } )
18. exf3
18. Kxg7
19. f4{ White continues to play a model game against any kind of Benko Gambit. He cannot advance his queenside majority directly. But he can exchange pawns in the center, open lines, and once more pieces start exchanging, eventually the queenside pawns count. }
19. Qa6( 19...exf4 20.g4! { Before recapturing on  f4 , White kicks the bishop away from the hanging  d3 -pawn. }20...Be6 21.Qxf4±  )
20. fxe5
20. dxe5
21. Na4{ Now the  c5 -pawn becomes a target and Black's pawns are no safer than White's. }
21. Nd7
