33. Bd5{ White consolidates his extra pawn. This is another one of those positions that only a computer can be stupid enough to call equal. It insists this position is very close to a draw, giving White +0.2. In human terms, the game is totally over. There is no way at all Black will be able to sit calmly and perfectly defend against every single idea and coordination White can try to start moving his a-pawn up the board. Even a player as strong as MVL lasted all of 3 moves before becoming hopelessly lost. }
33. Bxd5
34. Qe5+
34. f6( 34...Kg8 { The machine wants this one. }35.Qxd5 Qa3± { According to the computer, this is almost equal. I'm reasonably confident that with White, I would beat Carlsen from here 10 times in a row. And I am 100% certain that I would lose it with Black 10 times in a row. } )
35. Qxd5
35. h5{ It's a testament to how practically impossible Black's position is to defend that attempting to trade pawns and open lines to give checks loses immediately. }
